<P>
February 21, 1994, Monday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 8; Column 3; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
335 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCOPE IS A THREAT TO RIVER PLANNING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Supervisors Mike Antonovich (Los Angeles) and Maggie Kildee (Ventura) have 
appointed a 25-member steering committee to develop a management and 
enhancement plan for the Santa Clarita River. 
</P>
<P>
 This long-term cooperative planning effort for the river has been jeopardized 
by the actions of one of the groups represented on the committee.The committee 
members represent the various interested parties including federal, state and 
local regulatory agencies; businesses; environmentalists; farmers; cities; 
counties, and property owners. 
</P>
<P>
 A fundamental underlying principle is that development of the plan will not be 
used to delay ongoing environmental permitting of farming and business 
activities. This was agreed upon at the committee's first meeting and discussed 
again at its Oct. 20, 1993, meeting in Piru. 
</P>
<P>
 The ability to obtain environmental permits is crucial to farmers, property 
owners and businesses to protect their properties and livelihoods from the 
erosive forces of the river. Without the appropriate permits from regulatory 
agencies, these people can lose major portions if not all of their income, 
citrus groves, crops, land and businesses. 
</P>
<P>
 The Santa Clarita Organization for Planning the Environment (SCOPE) has now 
threatened the future of this river planning. SCOPE is represented on the 
committee by Friends of the Santa Clara River, a coalition of 
environmentalists. In direct contradiction to the agreement, Lynn Plambeck, 
first vice president of SCOPE, wrote the Army Corps of Engineers on Dec. 19, 
1993, stating, "Permits should be delayed until after the River Task Force has 
had a chance to develop its Management Plan." 
</P>
<P>
 Once again SCOPE and Ms. Plambeck have demonstrated their disregard for human 
safety and welfare. This group's environmental objective cannot be so important 
that it justifies ignoring families' livelihoods and exposing property and 
lives to risks from the river's flooding. 
</P>
<P>
 JAMES M. HARTER 
