<HEADLINE>
<P>
FUMES COMING FROM PATIENT CAUSE DOCTOR, NURSE TO FAINT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A doctor and nurse treating a patient in cardiac arrest were felled by fumes 
coming from the patient, and the hospital was forced to close its emergency 
room, authorities said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 The doctor and nurse were in stable condition at Riverside General Hospital, 
nursing supervisor Dolly Suban said.Four other medical staff members were 
treated and released at area hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
 The 31-year-old female patient -- who had been undergoing chemotherapy cancer 
treatment at home -- died. An autopsy was pending. 
</P>
<P>
 Fumes from the patient forced Riverside General to move seven emergency room 
patients into a parking lot Saturday night. Four patients were transferred to 
other hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials said the doctor and nurse were drawing blood from the woman when 
they noticed white crystals in it and smelled a substance like ammonia. Then 
they passed out. 
</P>
<P>
 Their names were not released. 
</P>
