WEST HILLS MAN ACCIDENTALLY SHOOTS FRIEND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 20-year-old West Hills man showing off a .22-caliber rifle to a group of 
friends Sunday accidentally shot a 17-year-old in the face, critically wounding 
him, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 The unidentified victim, also from West Hills, was taken to Northridge 
Hospital Medical Center, where he underwent a CAT scan to determine whether the 
bullet had penetrated his brain, said Los Angeles Police Lt. Jeff Hulet. 
</P>
<P>
 Russel Rayburn, 20, was booked on suspicion of possession of a firearm with an 
obliterated serial number, Hulet said. Possession of such a weapon is a felony, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Rayburn was at his parents' house showing the gun to about half a dozen 
friends when the gun went off at about 2:50 p.m., Hulet said. 
</P>
<P>
 Witnesses told police that Rayburn was "horsing around with the rifle," 
pointing it at different people in the room before the accident, Hulet said. 
</P>
<P>
 Hulet said the wounded teen-ager was shot from a distance of 10 to 12 feet. 
"He's very lucky to be alive." 
</P>
